segments.text: Go ahead.
You were talking about the problem.
We probably had 20 somewhat significant things in 27 years, and that's nothing.
The story I was going to relate is we had a gentleman who had worked for us for probably four or five years while we were in school here.
He went to Kentucky.
He had still yet to graduate, I think.
He went to Kentucky and was working in their program.
He was going to work in their program because his wife was working full time for them.
And he went out to officiate his first night of intramurals.
And he called us in that night.
He called Mike, who he worked with here.
Mike was a full-time staff member.
He called Mike.
He says, it's a war zone up here.
I can't believe how many fights we've had.
And our kids take their sport seriously.
But just like I was saying early on, they respect the game itself.
They respect the people.
we we have an opportunity for students to handle protests all the way there's an appeals process all the way up to the president really
But one of the intermediate steps is to what we call the recreational course advisory committee.
We haven't heard a protest in three or four years.
And we've done better at accommodating and handling things on site, which is where it should be handled.
But we always want to have that avenue of appeals there.
You know, I can remember when we first started here, we'd have one, two cases a week.
In Austin, when I was there, we had three hours of cases every week.
Every week.
It never stopped.
And it has just dwindled.
Part of it is we're looking better at handling things on-site.
Part of it is, you know, our kids are just so good about working with us.
Ever had a mama or a daddy call you, ask for a special favor?
Not really, not really.
It's not like a necessity of life, like the rest is all wrong or something.
Yeah, yeah.
Have there been any missed, now that you look back, any opportunities that were missed?
Yeah, there was probably various times that
I wish we had built this building earlier, but in retrospect, I'm glad we waited, because we learned a lot from other people.

I mean, the missed opportunity was for all those students in the meantime that didn't have the opportunity to be in this facility, because what we had back then was by no means close to accommodating their need.
And that showed up when we went from 250,000 participations to 1,250,000.
That's how huge the need was.
We kind of knew it was there.
We didn't think it was quite that big.
And again, if you were building this building today, there are not many changes you'd make, if any.
The only thing I, the only thing, one of the things that we tried very hard to do was to understand what facilities we had, what facilities we need, because there was a limit on money.
And we tried to handle that.
What we're seeing now is those facilities over there are
are being remodeled into classrooms and laboratories will lose some space and we're probably going to have to add out here.
But that's happened over time.
We didn't know that was going to happen at that point in time.
All right.
I'm nearing the downside in terms of questions I can think of.
Who are the key staff associates that you, over this 27 years, that you would want to thank most?
Tom Reber.
Tom Reber.
R-E?
R-E-B-E-R.
He's my senior associate director now.
He hasn't been here the longest, but he's really...
He has a commitment to the profession.
He has a commitment to Aggies in a big way.
He's done an outstanding job.
James Walford, who's been here the longest.
Then Rick Hall, just celebrating, starting his 21st or 22nd year.
And Rick's doing an outstanding job for us now.
Paula Opal.
How do you spell that name?
O-P-A-L.
Mike Walter, James Nash, you can kind of go down the list.
There's probably 15 people that have been here 12 or more years.
All right, what about people outside the intramural force that you would?
There's some other people that were here, Jim Jeter.
Jim Jeter was an assistant director then an associate director and then he went to the association of former students, was with them for a long time.
He gave us a lot.
Tom Weiss was here and then went up to Texas Tech.
Somebody have a message here?
All right, and then the administrator types that you most would want to thank.
John Colas, Carl Landis.
Carl Landis is probably number one.
He was a very special person.
It was his decision to bring me here, and thank goodness he saw past my long hair that I was okay.
But John Colas, Maryland Southerners.
fantastic support since we since he came in things are really going smooth with him as our as our leader chuck mccann was for all the stuff that he did when he was in the vice president's office
We would have had a hard time, both Carl Landis and I, and Leonard Ponder trying to get recreation and physical education happening without his support.
We would have run out of space.
Now, you and I would both agree, too, if we were a jury, we could accuse Chuck McCandless of being a biased observer.
Of course he is.
We like that.
That's right.
Let's see.
Let's make believe now that you're the consultant that has been brought in
to look forward for intramurals here at Texas A&M?
What advice would you give to anyone regarding the future here?
I think the groundwork is pretty well laid here.

many people say that we have the best program and the best facility in the country i think what we have to guard against is complacency and i think i think this staff has to continue to ask students what it is that they need they have to continue to look outside of this realm and see what is good and what is happening i think they need to evaluate the needs for
indoor facilities in relationship to what's happening with some of the other facilities we use.
Do we add on to this facility or build satellite facilities?
Some of those questions we're talking about right now.
We need to continue to upgrade our outdoor facilities because they're not up to this standard.
And we need to
And the whole benchmarking thing is part of showing others what we probably already know.
But that's important that you have the documentation for that.
Okay, next last question.
Let's make believe that someone walked up to you and gave you a check for a million dollars with one requirement.
You must pass it on to A&M, but you decide what use would be made.
What would you want that?
In other words, if you could make a very meaningful gift to A&M, for what purpose would you want that gift used?
Anything.
You know, in reality, it's still the most important place to put money in these universities and scholarships.
Okay.
For how do you select ?
Oh, it's still the most important.
I just had an executive director search for student financial aid, and that's still the most important place.
The students who
We have the ability, but not the money for tenure.
That's the most important question.
The rest of us can...
I think our students will endow this facility with their trust and their money in the future.
I don't think that's something we need to worry about.
That was a good line.
Use that.
Use that.
Endow this with their trust.
That's a good description of the feeling here.
What feelings do you hold in your heart today for Texas A&M?
It's the most important place in the world to me, other than my home.
Texas A&M has given me a fantastic opportunity to do that.
I think the work that I do is the most important work.
And that's helping people to create a healthy lifestyle.
I think the opportunity of doing that may be better than any of the physicians.
It's given me the opportunity to express myself with very few limitations.
It's the opportunity to deliver programs to them with very few limitations.
I think we've kept that trust and for reasonable costs.
I can't imagine anybody having a better run it at a job than I had.
I plan on being here another 15 years too if my health holds up.
Hopefully I'll be creative the whole time that I'm here.
I've had the opportunity to
to start with a good program and take it where I thought it needed to go based on my best and I've had the support of, without, I had support all the 27 years.
I anticipated the time to come.
I don't know how much more you can ask out of a job than that.
You know, I see
to get to this point in their life when they're hoping to retire.
I'm hoping to stay working.
It's just too much fun.
And that's the way it should be.
That's the kind of thing we're trying to create here, too.
But A&M has given me that.
I'm not sure I could get that anyplace else.
It's just a special place.
It is an institution of higher education that has a family sense.
that we're going to help each other and do for each other and if we work together, we can all be better.
And that's just kind of what I feel about it.
And that's where, you know, I probably didn't
I didn't do this very well when I first came here, but after 25 years you get to the point where you can find, you can see wind winds.
And that's been the real fun in the last few years is to see wind wind situations where other people see wind winds or nobody winds.
And that's what's really becoming fun now.
